{
  "answer": "In Cynewulf's *Juliana*, the saint is confined by the pagan reeve Eleusius to a man-made dungeon (*neowle* / \"prison-house\"), barred with a bolt \"a work of hammers,\" where she remains steadfast, praising Christ amid shadows as the Holy Spirit comforts her.[^1] The strongest line evoking this: \"Then with its bolt, the dungeon door / was barred shut, a work of hammers.\"\n\nIn \"The Wife's Lament\" (ch. 3 of *Old English Elegies*), the speaker—a wife separated from her lord by kin-feud—is commanded to dwell \"under an oak tree in this earth-cave\" (*eorðscrafu* / \"earth-cave\"), an ancient, overgrown natural hollow amid dim dales and briars, where she weeps endless exile-sorrow alone each dawn.[^2] The strongest line evoking this: \"under an oak tree in this earth-cave.\"\n\n**Framings:** Juliana's is hagiographic—urban, imposed by hostile authority, temporary, and spiritually triumphant (devil interrogated, faith unyielding). The wife's is elegiac—rural/natural, self-imposed by exile-circumstance, perpetual, and psychologically desolate (no divine aid, only grim endurance). \n\nNeither framing leaves room for the other. Juliana's dungeon-prison rejects natural isolation (no groves, earth-halls, or spousal woe; it's juridical/theological). The wife's earth-cave rejects man-made incarceration (no bolts, guards, or saintly defiance; it's organic, feuds-driven limbo).\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, ch. 1 [paragraphs](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-8666d0).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 3 [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/#p-c1cc32).",
